The data set utilized for this set of questions studies the remission survival times on 42 leukemia patients, half of whom get a certain new treatment therapy and the other half of whom get a standard treatment therapy. The exposure variable of interest is treatment status (Rx = 0 if new treatment, Rx = 1 if standard treatment). Two other variables for control as potential confounders are log white blood cell count (i.e., logwbc) and sex. Event status is defined by the relapse variable (0 if censored, 1 if relapse). (The data set is available online and can be imported with the following code).

#Import anderson data file
anderson<-read.delim("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nazzstat/SurvivalData/master/ander", header=TRUE)

#Add in column names
names(anderson)<-c("survtime","relapse","sex","logwbc","rx")
  1. Suppose we wish to describe KM curves for the variable logwbc in order for us to understand whether white blood count relates to survival time. Suppose we categorize logwbc into three categories - low (0–2.30), medium (2.31–3.00), and high (>3.00). State your conclusions based on your visual assessment of the KM curves.
anderson <- anderson %>% 
  mutate(logwbc.cat=ifelse(logwbc<2.31,"low",
                           ifelse(logwbc>3,"high",
                                  ifelse(logwbc>2.3,"medium","error"))))
model1 <- survfit(Surv(survtime,relapse)~logwbc.cat, data=anderson)
ggsurvplot(model1, conf.int=TRUE)

Visually, the survival curves of the high and low categories are different, with no overlap in the 95% CIs. The survival curves of the low category compared to the medium category and the high category compared to the medium category are visually different, but there is some overlap in the 95% CIs (with the overlap between the medium and high categories being most noticeable).

  1. What do you conclude about whether or not the three survival curves vary significantly.
survdiff(Surv(survtime,relapse)~logwbc.cat, data=anderson, rho=0)

There is a significant difference in the survival curves for those in the different categories of logwbc (\(\chi^2\)=26.4, p-value > .001).

  1. Next consider the data set std available through the KMsurv package. This data considers times to reinfection for patients with sexually transmitted diseases. Under investigation are gonorrhea and chlamydia. These diseases are of special interest because they are often asymptomatic in the female, and, if left untreated, can lead to complications including sterility. Both of these diseases can be easily prevented and effectively treated. Therefore, it is a mystery why the incidence of these diseases remain high in several sub populations. One theory is that a core group of individuals experience reinfections. thereby, serving as a natural reservoir of the disease organism and transferring the disease to uninfected individuals. The purpose of this study is to identify the factors which are related to time until reinfection. If the factors related to a greater risk of reinfection can be identified, then, interventions could be targeted to those individuals who are at the greatest risk for reinfection. We will explore this data set more in a future homework assignment.
data(std)
  1. Construct the KM survival curves to compare the risk of reinfection for participants who always use condoms versus those who do not always use condoms (that is, clump together the sometimes and never participants into one category).
std <- std %>% mutate(condom.cat=ifelse(condom==1, 1, 0))
model2a <- survfit(Surv(time,rinfct)~condom.cat, data=std)
ggsurvplot(model2a, conf.int=TRUE)

  1. Is there is a significant difference in the survival curves between the two groups above?

  1. Construct and interpret a 95% confidence interval to compare the median survival time of participants who always wear condoms versus those who do not.
model2a
## Call: survfit(formula = Surv(time, rinfct) ~ condom.cat, data = std)

The median survival time for those who do not always wear a condom is 698 units of time (CI: 592-803). Approximately half of the participants go without reinfection for at least 698 units of time, with a lower bound of the expected real population not being reinfected of 592 units of time, and an upper bound of 803 units of time.

The median survival time for those who do always wear a condom is 788 units of time (CI: 307-NA, there is no upper bound on the 95% CI). Approximately half of the participants go without reinfection for at least 788 units of time, with a lower bound of the expected real population not being reinfected of 307 units of time, and an infinite upper bound where enough patients were not reinfected during the study it is difficult to determine an upper limit on the 95% Confidence Interval.

  1. What can be said about the probability that someone from the population of interest (for those who always wear condoms versus those who do not) will not be reinfected after 1 year?
options(max.print=10000000)
summary(model2a)

The 95% Confidence interval for the proportion of people who do not always wear a condom who will survive past 367 days (the closest data we have to 365 days) is 0.607 - 0.683. This indicates that the probability of surviving past 367 days is .644 and we are 95% confident that between 60.7 and 68.3 percent of the population will survive beyond 367 days.

The 95% Confidence interval for the proportion of people who always wear a condom who will survive past 307 days (the closest data we have to 365 days) is 0.487 - 0.796. This indicates that the probability of surviving past 307 days is .623 and we are 95% confident that between 48.7 and 79.6 percent of the population will survive beyond 307 days.

  2. Consider the data set ‘bfeed’ available through the `KMsurv’ package. It is also available through the github url. The data consists of the information from 927 first-born children to mothers who chose to breastfeed their children and who have complete information for all variables of interest. The number of weeks until infant was weaned (duration) was recorded and whether or not weaning completed during study period was also recorded (delta). There are several covariates that are also available.

  1. Consider the data set `burn infection’ available through the github url. The study began to evaluate a protocol change in disinfectant practices for patient’s treated with severe burns. Control of infection remains a prominent component of burn management. The purpose of this study is to compare a routine bathing care method (initial surface decontamination with 10% povidone-iodine followed with regular bathing with Dial soap) with a body-cleansing method using 4% chlorhexidine gluconate. Medical records of patients treated during the 18-month study period provided information on burn wound infections and other medical information.
burn_infection<-read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nazzstat/SurvivalData/master/burn_infection.csv")
  • Z1: Treatment (0=routine bathing, 1=body cleansing)
  • Z2: Gender (0=male, 1=female)
  • Z3: Burn Type (1=chemical, 2=scald, 3=electric, 4= ame)
  • T1: Time to infection or censorship
  • D1: Infection (1=yes, 0=no)
  1. Construct a model that assesses the relationship of hazards of based on the variables treatment, gender, and burn type.

The model for males does not converge, I would try subsetting the data by condom use next.

The model for females does converge, and the PH assumptions appear to be fine. The expected hazards ratio for those in the treatment group are increased by a factor of 1.70 compared to those in the control group (\(\hat{HR}\)=1.70, p-value=.111), the hazards ratio for those who have a scald are 40.5% lower than those who have a chemical burn (\(\hat{HR}\)=.595, p-value=.437), the hazards ratio for those who have an electric burn are 61.6% lower than those who have a chemical burn (\(\hat{HR}\)=.384, p-value=.275), and the hazards ratio for those who have a flame burn are 21.8% lower than for those who have a chemical burn (\(\hat{HR}\)=.792, p-value=.645). None of these are statistically significant
